<a href="https://tinyurl.com/28rhj6ak" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/28rhj6ak</a>

@Strudel Dad 

I think that in cases like these, it's not always what you say, but how you say it, and how, regardless of intent, the person you're addressing it to receives it, regardless of the "facts".  Here, the native woman just didn't like it, so the employer should have just stopped using it.  It's like if your name is Thomas and someone insists on calling you Tom, and you don't like it.  Maybe because you're a Junior, and they call your dad Tom, and you Thomas.  "Tom" doesn't feel like it's your name.  Even though most Thomases are fine being called Tom, you just don't like it, so the person calling you Tom should just stop.  (Note that the puzzle today was constructed by Jeff and Jeffrey.)

Still, calling someone by a name he or she doesn't like is not an actionable offense...at least not in Nova Scotia, I guess.

@Strudel Dad and @Steve L

Our son Nathaniel has endlessly been called/referred to as  NATE....which is short for 'Nathan,' which is NOT his name.  No matter how often we say, "Nat, Natty, etc." they don't catch on.  Nat was too shy or too polite to correct them...but it bugged me.  (He was named for his grand-dad, my father.)  
It's just disrespectful at base, to ignore name preferences.

